00:11:58.363 --> 00:12:00.910
But when you see a guy
come in, muscle belt,

00:12:00.910 --> 00:12:05.530
shaved head, like legit SS
Nazi tattoos on his arms,

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:06.100
you would--

00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:06.640
you know?

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:07.600
I'm on his kill list.

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:10.450
I usually would step
back and be like, oh.

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:12.880
He was the one driving
me home at night

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:18.540
to make sure I got home
safe, so unexpected allies.

00:12:18.540 --> 00:12:23.100
He is obviously no longer
a Nazi sympathizer.

00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:24.870
He's very much a very
changed creature.

00:12:24.870 --> 00:12:25.980
But--

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:27.600
JULIEN FINLAY: Let
me go back on the--

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:29.100
FINLAY WILSON: --he's an
interesting little social

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:31.140
feature, who yoga and
mindfulness actually

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:34.230
brought him to stand as an
ally for me, which was lovely.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:34.980
JULIEN FINLAY: OK.

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:36.060
I think Nazian allyship--

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:36.390
FINLAY WILSON: That's
a different thing.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:38.015
JULIEN FINLAY: --could
be a great talk.

00:12:38.015 --> 00:12:39.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.850
But thank you for
sharing this, Finlay.

00:12:42.850 --> 00:12:47.910
And when I think of reaction
of putting yourself out there,

00:12:47.910 --> 00:12:49.950
I know Aoife, you had
a different experience

00:12:49.950 --> 00:12:53.520
whenever you came out at work.

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:55.800
I'd like you, if you're OK,
sharing this story of you

00:12:55.800 --> 00:12:57.600
coming out at work
at MasterCard,

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:02.370
but also somehow comparing this
reaction you had when you came

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:05.640
out at work to when you
were maybe coming out,

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:08.160
talking more about
your coming out online.

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:09.400
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah, sure.

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:11.050
So it was about two years ago.

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:16.440
Actually, it was 2016,
where I came out as Aoife.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:20.539
I mean, I spoke to my HR
manager before I came out.

00:13:20.539 --> 00:13:22.080
And at that time,
I h ad been working

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:25.460
with MasterCard for about
four years at that stage.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:27.690
And so I told her
that I was transgender

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:30.240
and that I wanted to transition
within the workplace.

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:33.330
And needless to say, I
think this was quite a shock

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:35.240
for my HR manager.

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:37.500
And she'd be the first
person to admit that.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:39.990
And I think she
said at that time

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:42.210
that she didn't know if we
had any policies in place.

00:13:42.210 --> 00:13:44.400
She'd never encountered this
in her HR career before.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:45.858
She'd never
encountered anybody who

00:13:45.858 --> 00:13:49.110
was transgender and didn't know
basically how to sort of handle

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:49.840
the situation.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:53.050
But the first thing she did
was she gave me a hug and says,

00:13:53.050 --> 00:13:53.550
yep.

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:54.990
OK, we'll do this.

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:56.400
Let's get through this week.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:59.820
And we agreed that we
would meet every week

00:13:59.820 --> 00:14:03.870
to sort of plan out a sort of
a roadmap, where things that--

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:09.300
who would I tell, when would
I tell them, badge changes,

00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:12.540
email address changes, all
these sort of little things

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:15.000
that you have to think about
if you're coming back to work

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.749
from one gender to another.

00:14:17.749 --> 00:14:19.290
And you know, I'd
love to say that it

00:14:19.290 --> 00:14:21.780
was a difficult process,
and we had to fight battles,

00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:23.980
and we knew we were
really strong about it.

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:26.400
But to be honest,
it was quite easy.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:30.240
I mean, changing my
name on the system

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:33.920
was just me logging into one
of our software applications

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:35.220
and just changing my name.

00:14:35.220 --> 00:14:37.511
And it just filtered down
through the system, you know?

00:14:37.511 --> 00:14:40.620
So it was quite easy
in that respect.

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:47.330
And we agreed that I would come
back to work in January, 2016,

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:48.680
as Aoife.

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:52.340
And I said, well, who
do we need to tell?

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:54.720
What way do we want
to handle this?

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:57.701
And we agreed that I would tell
some colleagues and some team

00:14:57.701 --> 00:14:58.200
members.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:00.650
I would tell my manager.

00:15:00.650 --> 00:15:01.400
But that was it.

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:02.900
We didn't need to
tell anybody else,

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:04.620
because it was nobody
else's business.

00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:06.360
You know, if somebody
comes out as gay,

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:10.290
you don't go, oh, let's announce
it to the entire company.

00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:11.790
So there was no
big announcement,

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:13.860
that, oh, Aoife is
coming back in January.

00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:17.910
And she will be a
different person.

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:19.690
So it was quite easy
in that respect.

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:22.277
I mean, also word of
mouth will get around.

00:15:22.277 --> 00:15:23.610
The grapevine will do its thing.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:26.647
And people are going
to find out, so--

00:15:26.647 --> 00:15:28.230
JULIEN FINLAY: And
when you come back?

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:32.190
AOIFE MARTIN: And when I
came back in January, 2016,

00:15:32.190 --> 00:15:33.960
I clearly remember
my first day back.

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.460
I was very, very nervous.

00:15:35.460 --> 00:15:38.500
And only a handful of people
knew this was happening.

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:40.230
And I got into the
office very early.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:43.737
And I sat behind my monitor,
just like I sort of just

00:15:43.737 --> 00:15:46.320
crouched down and just sort of
hoped most people wouldn't even

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.090
notice.

00:15:48.090 --> 00:15:50.490
And a friend of mine said,
well, I hope your day is just

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:51.172
weirdly normal.

00:15:51.172 --> 00:15:52.630
And I said, if it's
weirdly normal,

00:15:52.630 --> 00:15:54.510
I'll be happy with
that, you know?

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:57.331
And a few people come
over throughout the day

00:15:57.331 --> 00:15:59.580
who had known this was
happening, just to wish me luck

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:01.170
and to say, well
done sort of thing.

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:03.740
And then when I came back
from lunch on that day,

00:16:03.740 --> 00:16:06.510
there was a big bunch of
flowers that my HR manager

00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:11.620
had arranged to send, which was
such a lovely, lovely touch.

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:13.410
I wasn't expecting it at all.

00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:16.050
And it said, from
everyone at MasterCard,

00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:17.940
accept these flowers
to us, which was

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:19.260
such a lovely, sweet message.

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:22.260
And I took a photo
of the flowers.

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:23.940
And I put this on Twitter.

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:26.719
And the reaction was huge.

00:16:26.719 --> 00:16:28.760
We had an interview with
the "Irish Independent."

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:31.560
We spoke on a program on
Newstalk for a documentary.

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:33.360
And it just went viral.

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:36.630
So that's where my
activism started

00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:39.092
to kick in and where I
thought, OK, I can actually

00:16:39.092 --> 00:16:40.050
make a difference here.

00:16:40.050 --> 00:16:42.120
I can actually try and
speak about transitions

00:16:42.120 --> 00:16:45.690
and make people aware
of these issues.

00:16:45.690 --> 00:16:49.230
So their of reaction
was very, very positive.

00:16:49.230 --> 00:16:53.640
Online reaction has been
negative and positive as well.

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:56.370
So it just varies from who's
sort of doing it, you know?

00:16:56.370 --> 00:16:57.720
I mean, I can talk about
the negative stuff now

00:16:57.720 --> 00:16:58.320
if you want or--

00:16:58.320 --> 00:16:59.361
JULIEN FINLAY: Please do.

00:16:59.361 --> 00:17:02.940
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah,
so I initially,

00:17:02.940 --> 00:17:04.890
before I came out in
MasterCard, I sort of

00:17:04.890 --> 00:17:06.540
came out on Twitter before.

00:17:06.540 --> 00:17:08.579
And that was hugely
positive for me.

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:10.619
And a lot of people were
very, very accepting.

00:17:10.619 --> 00:17:13.240
But then, of course, there are
people who aren't as accepting.

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:15.829
And like I remember
once, waking up one day

00:17:15.829 --> 00:17:17.490
and just checking
my Twitter feed.

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:19.710
And somebody had a
posted a photograph

00:17:19.710 --> 00:17:22.619
of me, one of my pictures,
and with the word man scrolled

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:25.380
across it, and just had sent
that to all of her followers.

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:27.390
You sort of go--

00:17:27.390 --> 00:17:29.490
so I sort of took
the same photograph

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:31.890
with the word man
scrawled across it

00:17:31.890 --> 00:17:33.660
and wrote W-O in front of it.

00:17:33.660 --> 00:17:36.600
And I posted that
once to all followers.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:40.140
And it's quite hurtful.

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:44.180
It's something you have to
build up a thicker skin about.

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:46.059
Because there's a
lot of negativity

00:17:46.059 --> 00:17:47.850
out there, especially
towards trans people,

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:50.850
especially more so in the
UK than in Ireland, I think.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:53.340
And there's an awful lot of
online hate about trans people

00:17:53.340 --> 00:17:55.050
at the moment, a
lot of negativity

00:17:55.050 --> 00:17:57.490
in the press about trans people.

00:17:57.490 --> 00:18:00.150
And I think we need
to combat that.

00:18:00.150 --> 00:18:02.360
And I get misgendered
all the time.

00:18:02.360 --> 00:18:03.350
I get called he.

00:18:03.350 --> 00:18:06.580
I get accused of
all sorts of things.

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:08.880
But at this stage, I've
got a pretty thick skin.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.820
You don't go through
life being trans and not

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:12.990
getting a thick skin by
the end of it, you know?

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:15.500
JULIEN FINLAY: And that's, as
I say, you really speak out.

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:18.260
And you accepted that skin.

00:18:18.260 --> 00:18:20.280
And you actually are making it--

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:24.130
you're hardening it
by defending others.

00:18:24.130 --> 00:18:26.080
To all of you, who
has, to some degree,

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:30.760
ever experienced online hate or
cyberbullying or harassment--

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:32.650
maybe not to their
extent, but something

00:18:32.650 --> 00:18:35.530
you did not like reading
or seeing or receiving?

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:40.160
Yeah.

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:41.330
So it happens.

00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:45.410
It doesn't have to be changing
your name or your badge

00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:48.330
or having 50 million
views on you,

00:18:48.330 --> 00:18:54.420
but to create such a backlash.

00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:59.434
You both talk about
campaigns against yourselves.

00:18:59.434 --> 00:19:01.600
And the Google part of your
campaign, it's something

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:02.260
you set up.

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:02.800
You think.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.920
You plan.

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:08.280
Would that be the case for
you as in a group of people

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:13.000
or a person who really take
their time, their money,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.530
their energy to be hateful
and use internet as a media

00:19:16.530 --> 00:19:18.450
to develop that hate?

00:19:23.270 --> 00:19:25.700
FINLAY WILSON: I'm not sure
it necessarily-- so campaign,

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:28.310
almost just describing more than
one person kind of getting in

00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:30.643
on it, not necessarily they're
spending money behind it.

00:19:30.643 --> 00:19:34.760
But certainly, I will see
people leave incredibly damaging

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:36.680
comments and will
tag friends who

00:19:36.680 --> 00:19:38.060
obviously share those views.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:40.470
And then the bombarding starts.

00:19:40.470 --> 00:19:42.950
And that can usually start
to really snowball things.

00:19:42.950 --> 00:19:44.533
Because you try and
block one of them.

00:19:44.533 --> 00:19:47.060
And then the accounts
start replicating.

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:51.230
So that can be
incredibly frustrating.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:55.840
But there is a resilience that
you have to develop to that.

00:19:55.840 --> 00:19:57.880
I mean, I ended up
having an argument

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:02.130
against Piers Morgan, which
I suppose was his campaign.

00:20:02.130 --> 00:20:04.750
Because he was
trying to diminish--

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:08.440
he re-shared the video about
male suicide and depression

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:12.160
that my twin brother and I
created and told us to man up.

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:14.149
And that was him
using his platform

00:20:14.149 --> 00:20:15.190
in a really negative way.

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:18.620
Because we were speaking
about coming out issues.

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:20.809
We were speaking about that
sort of identity crisis

00:20:20.809 --> 00:20:22.600
but also about male
suicide and depression.

00:20:22.600 --> 00:20:25.510
And he could have used his
platform for good, sharing it.

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:29.030
But instead, his campaign was
one of hate and derogatory.

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:32.709
So it's not just the
little grunt trolls

00:20:32.709 --> 00:20:34.000
that you need to watch out for.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.279
There are some people who really
do have campaigns against us.

00:20:37.279 --> 00:20:38.070
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah.

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:41.650
And there is an organization in
the UK called a Woman's Org--

00:20:41.650 --> 00:20:44.280
awomansplace.org, I
think it's called.

00:20:44.280 --> 00:20:47.470
And they're very
much anti-trans.

00:20:47.470 --> 00:20:48.870
And the UK at the moment--

00:20:48.870 --> 00:20:50.536
I don't know if you're
aware-- is trying

00:20:50.536 --> 00:20:52.780
to change their Gender
Recognition Act to allow

00:20:52.780 --> 00:20:54.210
trans people to self-identify.

00:20:54.210 --> 00:20:57.430
And this is something we
brought in in Ireland in 2015.

00:20:57.430 --> 00:21:00.910
And it hasn't caused
any issues whatsoever,

00:21:00.910 --> 00:21:03.970
whereas this year, there's
been a campaign in the UK

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:06.040
to push back.

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:08.730
The UK government opened
up a consultation process.

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:14.050
And this awomansplace.org has
had meetings in Parliament

00:21:14.050 --> 00:21:16.960
and has set up meetings in
town halls around the country

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:20.530
to advocate against changing
the Gender Recognition Act

00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:24.910
and to not allow trans people
in the UK to self-identify.

00:21:24.910 --> 00:21:28.490
And they tried to set up a
meeting in Dublin to actually,

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:30.670
to come over here and set
up a meeting in Dublin.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:33.055
And they were pretty much
given the short shrift.

00:21:33.055 --> 00:21:37.960
And a lot of Irish feminists
wrote an open letter,

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:40.120
saying that TERF
says that they're--

00:21:40.120 --> 00:21:45.790
TERF, that stands for
Trans-Exclusionary Radical

00:21:45.790 --> 00:21:47.830
Feminist.

00:21:47.830 --> 00:21:51.460
And so they wrote a letter,
saying TERF says, and saying,

00:21:51.460 --> 00:21:52.924
you're not welcome
in this country.

00:21:52.924 --> 00:21:53.590
This is Ireland.

00:21:53.590 --> 00:21:55.930
We support trans
people in this country.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:57.840
And we don't want you
guys coming over here.

00:21:57.840 --> 00:22:02.440
And it was signed by well over
1,000 cisgender feminist women

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:04.150
who were pro trans rights.

00:22:04.150 --> 00:22:06.762
So it's great.

00:22:06.762 --> 00:22:08.470
It was great to see
that, that these guys

00:22:08.470 --> 00:22:09.553
weren't welcome over here.

00:22:09.553 --> 00:22:11.290
But they're quite
prominent in the UK.

00:22:11.290 --> 00:22:13.630
And they're getting a lot
of attention by the media.

00:22:13.630 --> 00:22:14.890
JULIEN FINLAY: How does it--

00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:17.020
when we talk, when we
think of this hate,

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:19.474
when we think of
the slurs, and sure,

00:22:19.474 --> 00:22:20.890
you have a hard
skin, both of you.

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:23.710
And you would also help
other people, I'm sure,

00:22:23.710 --> 00:22:26.220
who contact you and
may not have the voice

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:29.320
or may not have your courage.

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:32.410
So you are also counseling them.

00:22:32.410 --> 00:22:35.850
How does it affect yourself?

00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:39.240
How do you cope
with that in terms--

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:40.630
you mentioned mindfulness.

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:43.750
But it is a hard road
to take on when you just

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:48.350
want to be yourselves and
live on with your lives.

00:22:48.350 --> 00:22:50.160
How do you feel, both of you?

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:51.840
AOIFE MARTIN: [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:53.620
FINLAY WILSON: Sure.

00:22:53.620 --> 00:22:58.757
Certainly, I think to think
that the reaction is downplayed,

00:22:58.757 --> 00:22:59.590
like, yes, I'm here.

00:22:59.590 --> 00:23:01.840
Yes, I'm sort of standing
up and doing all this stuff.

00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:03.940
But when these
things come in, there

00:23:03.940 --> 00:23:05.440
is still that
overwhelming sensation

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:08.410
of not wanting to leave the
house, of feeling completely

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:13.270
slimed, and having that
really frustrating moment

00:23:13.270 --> 00:23:14.850
of questioning yourself.

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:17.770
And that's the worst
part, that worst part,

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:20.960
where actually your
self-acceptance wavers

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:22.550
in the face of that.

00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:26.150
And that, for me, is where
my yoga practice comes in.

00:23:26.150 --> 00:23:30.590
Because I almost need to
reset my Finlayism before

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:32.420
I then leave the door again.

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:34.520
So for me, my morning
yoga practice,

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:37.789
my time to do that reintegration
work so that when I go out,

00:23:37.789 --> 00:23:39.830
I don't just see the first
straight person I see,

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:41.390
think that they're going to
attack me and try and kill them

00:23:41.390 --> 00:23:42.782
first.

00:23:42.782 --> 00:23:44.670
Whew.

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:45.470
Yeah.

00:23:45.470 --> 00:23:47.249
Don't do that.

00:23:47.249 --> 00:23:48.040
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah.

00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:50.860
I mean, I think that
that's a very good point

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:52.630
about accepting yourself.

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:55.050
Because there is a lot
of negativity out there.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:57.880
And I always say the bravest
step a trans person can take

00:23:57.880 --> 00:23:59.650
is stepping across
that threshold,

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:02.840
stepping outside
the door in public--

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:05.560
not even just the first
time, nearly every time.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:07.930
Because you're putting
yourself out there.

00:24:07.930 --> 00:24:15.160
You are possibly visibly
trans and open to negativity.

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:18.460
I read all sorts of
crappy comments online.

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.640
And while I'm quite a
thick-skinned person,

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:23.380
it's the sheer volume
of it that just

00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:24.800
chips and chips and chips away.

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:26.860
And there are days where I
just god, oh, I just can't

00:24:26.860 --> 00:24:27.950
face going outside the door.

00:24:27.950 --> 00:24:29.410
And I don't want to
go outside the door.

00:24:29.410 --> 00:24:29.850
But I have to.

00:24:29.850 --> 00:24:30.670
I have to get up.

00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:31.734
I have to go to work.

00:24:31.734 --> 00:24:33.900
I work in an office where
everybody knows I'm trans.

00:24:33.900 --> 00:24:35.870
And everybody is cool with that.

00:24:35.870 --> 00:24:37.150
But it's still not easy.

00:24:37.150 --> 00:24:40.730
You know, it's still a
difficult thing to do.

00:24:40.730 --> 00:24:45.480
And I think that it's
just the sheer sort of--

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:48.460
as I was saying, just the
sheer volume of that hate.

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:50.230
It's not just, I can
handle one comment.

00:24:50.230 --> 00:24:51.646
I can handle a
number of comments.

00:24:51.646 --> 00:24:53.950
But when it's just drip,
drip, drip, that drip feed,

00:24:53.950 --> 00:24:55.990
eventually, it does chip
away at you sometimes.

00:24:55.990 --> 00:24:58.600
And I'm aware of
trans people in the UK

00:24:58.600 --> 00:25:01.720
who haven't left their
house in months, they said,

00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:04.150
because the negative
reaction from media,

00:25:04.150 --> 00:25:07.950
from people on the street,
from all sorts of things.

00:25:07.950 --> 00:25:11.545
And it's a pretty toxic
environment at times, you know?

00:25:11.545 --> 00:25:14.041
FINLAY WILSON: We were talking
about it in the green room.

00:25:14.041 --> 00:25:16.290
I teach in some of the island
communities in Scotland.

00:25:16.290 --> 00:25:17.665
And somebody comes
to me and said

00:25:17.665 --> 00:25:20.290
they hadn't seen a single
living person in over 30 days

00:25:20.290 --> 00:25:22.600
because they're trans
on this Scottish island.

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:26.130
And they just say they feel like
they just can't go anywhere.

00:25:26.130 --> 00:25:29.010
And so they just choose
to not see anyone.

00:25:29.010 --> 00:25:32.789
But I think the comments
that come in almost directly

00:25:32.789 --> 00:25:35.080
to our social media, they do
that almost daily chipping

00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:35.580
away.

00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:37.360
We do that small
practice of reintegration

00:25:37.360 --> 00:25:39.890
and then go back out
the door that morning.

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:41.980
But the more oppressive
thing is seeing the things

00:25:41.980 --> 00:25:42.896
in the larger picture.

00:25:42.896 --> 00:25:44.560
And we see America,
rights getting

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:46.870
stripped away left, right,
and center, and thinking,

00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:48.850
when's it going to come here?

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:50.770
When is this going
to happen here?

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:53.290
When am I going to get
discriminated against in a shop

00:25:53.290 --> 00:25:55.980
again?

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:58.620
JULIEN FINLAY: Do you feel
supported sometimes by others?

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:03.605
Or it's you against a big
wave that you may not--

00:26:03.605 --> 00:26:05.730
FINLAY WILSON: That's where
the education comes in.

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:11.640
Because even my family,
every single one of them,

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:17.190
straight, generations of
frustrating straight people.

00:26:17.190 --> 00:26:20.410
And that's not me saying
that if you're straight

00:26:20.410 --> 00:26:21.540
that you're frustrating.

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:26.022
But they live under
this shell, this bubble,

00:26:26.022 --> 00:26:28.230
where they're like, no, none
of that happens anymore.

00:26:28.230 --> 00:26:30.350
You're overreacting.

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:31.980
And they don't get
why I get angry.

00:26:31.980 --> 00:26:33.750
They don't get why I get upset.

00:26:33.750 --> 00:26:36.360
They don't get why sometimes I
phone my mum and I'm in tears.

00:26:36.360 --> 00:26:38.193
I'm like, do you see
what is happening here?

00:26:38.193 --> 00:26:43.620
Do you see how the rainbow world
is burning around the planet?

00:26:43.620 --> 00:26:46.770
When I go and teach in places
like Indonesia to be told,

00:26:46.770 --> 00:26:50.460
you need to really dial
everything you do down,

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:54.480
which see when you teach in
pink leggings, that's hard.

00:26:54.480 --> 00:26:55.180
That's hard.

00:26:55.180 --> 00:26:58.260
It's hard to do, all right?

00:26:58.260 --> 00:27:00.130
To not feel safe--

00:27:00.130 --> 00:27:02.670
I feel relatively
safe in Scotland.

00:27:02.670 --> 00:27:06.340
When I was teaching in Texas,
I did not feel safe, all right?

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:08.580
When I was teaching in
Indonesia, I didn't feel safe.

00:27:08.580 --> 00:27:11.670
But I kind of found
like a gay community who

00:27:11.670 --> 00:27:13.380
were like the rebel faction.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:15.510
It was nice to kind
of hang out with them.

00:27:15.510 --> 00:27:20.570
But that cloud of
oppression isn't going away.

00:27:20.570 --> 00:27:24.490
And actually, that one saps
me more than the daily.

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:30.627
JULIEN FINLAY: Do you want to
add something to this, Aoife?

00:27:30.627 --> 00:27:31.460
AOIFE MARTIN: Sorry.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:32.450
I lost my train of thought.

00:27:32.450 --> 00:27:33.616
What was the question again?

00:27:33.616 --> 00:27:34.440
[LAUGHS]

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:38.957
JULIEN FINLAY: Basically if
you feel supported, if you

00:27:38.957 --> 00:27:40.040
have people there for you?

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:40.550
AOIFE MARTIN: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:42.360
JULIEN FINLAY: If you
[INAUDIBLE] to combat?

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:42.640
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah.

00:27:42.640 --> 00:27:43.598
That's a good question.

00:27:43.598 --> 00:27:48.440
I mean, I have a lot of friends
who are very, very supportive.

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:51.157
Most of my friends would
be cisgender women.

00:27:51.157 --> 00:27:52.490
And they've totally accepted me.

00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:54.270
And we go for coffee.

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:54.770
We meet.

00:27:54.770 --> 00:27:56.270
We go for meals, et cetera.

00:27:56.270 --> 00:27:57.330
And it's great.

00:27:57.330 --> 00:27:59.090
But I think a lot
people just aren't

00:27:59.090 --> 00:28:02.300
aware of the constant sort
of drip feed of negativity

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:03.060
that's out there.

00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:06.170
I think, I hate to say,
but a lot of people

00:28:06.170 --> 00:28:08.630
live in sort of heterosexual,
cisgender bubble.

00:28:08.630 --> 00:28:12.890
And while they're
sort of tangentially

00:28:12.890 --> 00:28:15.740
aware of these issues happening,
because it's not affecting them

00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:18.020
directly, they're not aware
of how hurtful it can be

00:28:18.020 --> 00:28:20.760
and how difficult it
can be for trans people.

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:23.524
And I constantly say this.

00:28:23.524 --> 00:28:25.190
Look, if you have a
friend who is trans,

00:28:25.190 --> 00:28:29.180
if you have somebody in
your life who's trans,

00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:31.100
reach out and just
say, how are you doing?

00:28:31.100 --> 00:28:31.960
Is everything OK?

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:33.940
There's some shitty
stuff in the news.

00:28:33.940 --> 00:28:34.757
Are you OK?

00:28:34.757 --> 00:28:35.840
Are you feeling all right?

00:28:35.840 --> 00:28:36.740
Do you want to talk
about anything?

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:39.080
Do you just want to go for
a coffee and have a natter?

00:28:39.080 --> 00:28:42.050
So I think it's
just important just

00:28:42.050 --> 00:28:44.600
to be there, be supportive,
and just reach out when you can

00:28:44.600 --> 00:28:46.195
say, just let's go for coffee.

00:28:46.195 --> 00:28:47.570
JULIEN FINLAY:
That's a good one.

00:28:47.570 --> 00:28:49.280
That's valuable for
anyone, I would say, not

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:50.160
depending on their--

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:50.540
AOIFE MARTIN: Oops.

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:51.665
JULIEN FINLAY: You're good.

00:28:51.665 --> 00:28:53.870
It won't fall there--

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:56.120
to anyone, depending on
their identification.

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:58.790
But specifically
to some minorities,

00:28:58.790 --> 00:29:02.150
I think we would have to develop
a stronger sense of empathy,

00:29:02.150 --> 00:29:06.200
as in, oh, I'm aware Aoife may
not feel good today for X, Y,

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:09.470
Z reasons, or Finlay either.

00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:12.770
You both mentioned
that education and also

00:29:12.770 --> 00:29:16.580
the idea of a rebel
club, that where

00:29:16.580 --> 00:29:18.950
you could have seen the
internet for a while,

00:29:18.950 --> 00:29:23.072
like where the minorities
would live or develop or hide.

00:29:23.072 --> 00:29:24.530
Do you think that's
still the case?

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:25.946
Do you think the
internet is still

00:29:25.946 --> 00:29:28.130
a safe haven for minorities?

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:29.300
FINLAY WILSON: It's tricky.

00:29:29.300 --> 00:29:34.160
Because I see a lot of people
who give the guise of support

00:29:34.160 --> 00:29:37.064
online-- so for example,
if somebody sends me hate,

00:29:37.064 --> 00:29:39.230
like it's almost becoming
one of my favorite things,

00:29:39.230 --> 00:29:42.890
is just to publicly shame them.

00:29:42.890 --> 00:29:45.470
When that happens, it's always
the people in the rainbow

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:48.620
bubble that tell me to
not post that stuff,

00:29:48.620 --> 00:29:50.600
to actually stay quiet.

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:53.205
Because they have an
institutionalized oppression

00:29:53.205 --> 00:29:54.830
where they're like,
no, no, no, no, no.

00:29:54.830 --> 00:29:56.360
Don't talk about this.

00:29:56.360 --> 00:29:58.710
And that's from people who
it's also happening to.

00:29:58.710 --> 00:30:01.180
And it's a very strange,
like, oh, they've got us good.

00:30:01.180 --> 00:30:03.799
They've really got us
good, so to actually

00:30:03.799 --> 00:30:05.840
be able to speak to people
who will then actually

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:08.630
stand up and also be
happy to speak out

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:11.620
about that kind of thing.

00:30:11.620 --> 00:30:13.900
I would say that's
much rarer to find

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:17.360
that than to find the people
that will become apologists,

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:21.200
that will just say, no, no,
no, just don't think about it.

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:22.330
Don't talk about it.

00:30:22.330 --> 00:30:23.800
Certainly don't share it.

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:26.330
Certainly don't have
an opinion about it.

00:30:26.330 --> 00:30:27.382
Makes me sick.

00:30:27.382 --> 00:30:28.840
JULIEN FINLAY: But
you still share?

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:29.881
FINLAY WILSON: Of course.

00:30:33.692 --> 00:30:36.150
JULIEN FINLAY: Both of you,
have you ever posted something,

00:30:36.150 --> 00:30:37.970
and then you regretted
it and deleted,

00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:40.290
or have had double thoughts,
either because you thought

00:30:40.290 --> 00:30:42.490
you'd be hateful
or because you felt

00:30:42.490 --> 00:30:43.700
that was not your job to do?

00:30:46.146 --> 00:30:48.270
AOIFE MARTIN: Well, you
should see my drafts folder

00:30:48.270 --> 00:30:51.410
in Twitter, stuff I've
wanted to say but not said.

00:30:51.410 --> 00:30:54.120
And if ever I die, I'm hoping
one of my friends will log

00:30:54.120 --> 00:30:56.520
in and just delete
everything in there,

00:30:56.520 --> 00:31:00.532
stuff you wouldn't-- generally,
I'm quite careful because I

00:31:00.532 --> 00:31:02.490
know how it can affect
people because I've been

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:03.365
on the receiving end.

00:31:03.365 --> 00:31:06.351
I'm quite aware of what I say.

00:31:06.351 --> 00:31:08.100
I don't always--
sometimes, I do lash out.

00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:10.140
Sometimes I do say
something I regret later

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:12.930
or something I
shouldn't have said.

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:14.820
I'm also aware that
I have a platform

00:31:14.820 --> 00:31:18.600
and that there are younger
trans people possibly reading

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:19.410
what I write.

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:22.560
And I once wrote a
pretty negative article

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:25.500
about being trans, because
I was going through sort

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:26.850
of major dysphoria at the time.

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:31.710
And it was sort of like why it
sucks being trans, basically.

00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:33.420
And the article was published.

00:31:33.420 --> 00:31:35.130
But I actually had to email
the editor and say, look,

00:31:35.130 --> 00:31:37.088
could you just change
the headline on that just

00:31:37.088 --> 00:31:38.430
to make it sound less negative?

00:31:38.430 --> 00:31:40.350
I mean, he didn't change the
content of the article, which

00:31:40.350 --> 00:31:42.641
was fine, because that's how
I was feeling at the time.

00:31:42.641 --> 00:31:44.580
But rather than
calling the article,

00:31:44.580 --> 00:31:47.190
it sucks being trans, let's be
a bit more positive about it

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:50.490
and have something, rather than
having that negativity there.

00:31:50.490 --> 00:31:53.070
Because I do try to,
as much as I can,

00:31:53.070 --> 00:31:57.080
highlight the positive aspects
and just to usualize this

00:31:57.080 --> 00:31:59.160
and to say, look, it
is OK to be trans.

00:31:59.160 --> 00:32:01.173
There's nothing to be
ashamed about, you know?

00:32:01.853 --> 00:32:04.926
JULIEN FINLAY: Finlay,
do you regret your posts?

00:32:04.926 --> 00:32:07.300
FINLAY WILSON: Well, some
images that I've put up-- well,

00:32:07.300 --> 00:32:08.620
there was one time.

00:32:08.620 --> 00:32:10.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:13.280
I'd done this photo shoot
with my twin brother.

00:32:13.280 --> 00:32:14.200
And it was great.

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:14.784
It was lovely.

00:32:14.784 --> 00:32:16.658
And I thought, I'm just
going to chuck, like,

00:32:16.658 --> 00:32:17.650
70 images on Facebook.

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:19.108
And then I was
like, this one image

00:32:19.108 --> 00:32:20.340
has been shared 500 times.

00:32:20.340 --> 00:32:22.600
It's cause you can
see everything.

00:32:22.600 --> 00:32:23.510
I didn't know.

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:24.170
I had no clue.

00:32:24.170 --> 00:32:25.570
I regret that.

00:32:25.570 --> 00:32:29.260
But as for my responses
online, not so much-- but

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:32.020
I have shifted my
tactics for the people

00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:34.450
who leave hateful comments on
my Instagram in particular.

00:32:34.450 --> 00:32:36.460
Because I know there's--

00:32:36.460 --> 00:32:39.614
for example, I teach a group
of kids with additional support

00:32:39.614 --> 00:32:41.030
needs, like multiple
disabilities.

00:32:41.030 --> 00:32:42.910
And I know actually
daily, they check

00:32:42.910 --> 00:32:45.460
in to my Facebook to
see what poses I'm doing

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:46.960
and then see if
they can recreate it

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:49.530
in their classroom,
every single day.

00:32:49.530 --> 00:32:52.190
And so if they're seeing me
being really nasty to somebody

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:53.390
who's been really
nasty to me, it's

00:32:53.390 --> 00:32:54.723
not setting a very good example.

00:32:54.723 --> 00:32:57.200
So one of my new
favorites, it's like,

00:32:57.200 --> 00:33:01.640
oops, you're on the wrong
page, fingernail emoji.

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:05.240
And then you
usually would direct

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:08.030
the followers to be like, go
and send them a message for me.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:09.730
And I send in the troops.

00:33:09.730 --> 00:33:12.890
So I will leave them a little
bit like, whoops-a-daisy.

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:16.520
And then the troops go
in there and will usually

00:33:16.520 --> 00:33:19.860
do the critique work
for me without--

00:33:19.860 --> 00:33:22.220
it's not saying that I
won't go in and do the work.

00:33:22.220 --> 00:33:25.470
But it's me saying, I'm not
going to engage with you.

00:33:25.470 --> 00:33:28.080
But also, you're on my page.

00:33:28.080 --> 00:33:29.392
You must like what you see.

00:33:29.392 --> 00:33:31.732
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:32.909 --> 00:33:33.700
AOIFE MARTIN: Yeah.

00:33:33.700 --> 00:33:34.580
There is an argument.

00:33:34.580 --> 00:33:36.230
I mean, I've had
this sort of argue

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:37.850
with people, where
they say, just

00:33:37.850 --> 00:33:41.815
don't give them any limelight.

00:33:41.815 --> 00:33:42.360
And I agree.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:44.860
I mean, it's easy for people
to say that because they're not

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:45.860
the ones being attacked.

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:46.920
FINLAY WILSON: Yeah.

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:49.460
AOIFE MARTIN: And
sometimes, I will ignore.

00:33:49.460 --> 00:33:51.260
And I will just not
pass any remarks.

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:52.710
Or I will I will do what you do.

00:33:52.710 --> 00:33:53.880
I will send in the troops.

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:55.372
I will quote, tweet this.

00:33:55.372 --> 00:33:57.830
Look what this arsehole is out
there saying, sort of thing,

00:33:57.830 --> 00:34:01.640
and just let everybody
else do the hard work.

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:04.361
But I'm also aware that
since I came out at work,

